# WHAT IT IS
#   Tauraro is a compiled, statically-typed language with
#   Python-style indentation syntax that compiles to C and
#   then to native machine code via GCC or Clang.  The
#   pitch: Python's readability with performance close to
#   hand-written C.
#
#   Distinctive feature: Tauraro is **"the first programming
#   language with full bilingual keyword support"** — every
#   keyword has both an English and a Hausa equivalent.
#   Programs can be written in either language, or mixed
#   freely:
#
#     # English
#     def greet(name: str) -> str:
#         return f"Hello, {name}!"
#
#     # Hausa
#     aiki gaisawa(suna: str) -> str:
#         dawo f"Sannu, {suna}!"
#
#     def main():
#         print(greet("world"))
#         buga(gaisawa("duniya"))
#
#   Hausa keyword map (selected):
#     aiki = def                       aji  = class
#     dawo = return                    idan = if
#     buga = print                     karanta = read
#     samun = get                      sakawa = set
#     duba = check                     ...
#
#   Self-hosted compiler: every `.tr` file under `src/` is
#   itself Tauraro source — `tauraroc` builds itself.
#   Two codegen backends: emit C (default; passed through
#   GCC/Clang for portability) or LLVM IR (`--backend llvm`).
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from src/main.tr
#                       `print_usage()` text; extracted via
#                       `gh api repos/tauraro/tauraro/
#                       contents/src/main.tr`)
#
#   tauraroc <FILE.tr> [OPTIONS]
#
#   General:
#     --version                      Print version and exit
#                                    ("tauraroc v0.0.3")
#     --verbose                      Show all pipeline phases
#                                    (lex / parse / sema /
#                                    hir / codegen)
#
#   Pipeline emission:
#     --emit c                       Emit generated C code to
#                                    `build/` and stop
#     --emit ast                     Emit AST representation
#                                    and stop
#     --emit mir                     Emit MIR (mid-IR) basic
#                                    blocks and stop
#     --check                        Run semantic analysis
#                                    only (no codegen)
#     --run                          Compile and immediately
#                                    execute
#
#   Backend:
#     --backend llvm                 Use LLVM IR backend
#                                    instead of C (default
#                                    backend is C — GCC /
#                                    Clang / cc auto-
#                                    detected via
#                                    `detect_c_compiler()`)
#
#   Output / linking:
#     -o <PATH>                      Output executable name
#                                    (temp `.c` files are
#                                    deleted on success)
#     --link <PATH>                  Link an additional file
#                                    by path (`.c .o .a .dll
#                                    .lib .so`)
#     -l<NAME> | -l <NAME>           Link a library by name
#                                    (e.g. `-luser32 -lgdi32`)
#     --static                       Statically link the
#                                    output binary
#
#   Optimization:
#     -O0 / -O1 / -O2 / -O3          Optimization level
#                                    [default: -O2]
#     -Os                            Optimize for size
#
#   Cross-compilation:
#     --target <NAME>                Cross-compile for a
#                                    target platform.  Known
#                                    shorthands:
#                                      android-arm64
#                                      android-arm32
#                                      android-x86_64
#                                      android-x86
#                                      ios
#                                      ios-sim
#                                      linux-arm64
#                                      linux-arm32
#                                      linux-x86_64
#                                      linux-riscv64
#                                      windows-x64
#                                      windows-arm64
#                                      macos-arm64
#                                      macos-x86_64
#                                      embedded-arm
#                                      embedded-arm64
#                                      embedded-riscv32
#                                      embedded-riscv64
#                                      wasm
#                                      wasm-wasi
#                                    Or pass a raw LLVM
#                                    triple (e.g.
#                                    `aarch64-linux-gnu`).
#     --sysroot <PATH>               Override sysroot for the
#                                    cross-compiler
#
